i asked if this was a trust or a spot etf summaryits a trust the ishares bitcoin trust is a grantor trust, not an etf some key differences between the ishares bitcoin trust and a bitcoin spot etf the ishares bitcoin trust issues shares that represent fractional undivided interests in bitcoin held by the trust a spot bitcoin etf would hold bitcoin directly and its shares would represent an ownership interest in the etf itself the ishares bitcoin trust is not regulated or registered as an investment company under the investment company act of 1940 a spot bitcoin etf would have to register under this act and comply with its regulatory requirements the ishares bitcoin trust seeks to reflect the performance of the price of bitcoin before expenses, while a spot bitcoin etf would seek to track the spot price of bitcoin the ishares bitcoin trust is treated as a grantor trust for tax purposes this means that gains and losses from bitcoin sales flow through to shareholders a spot bitcoin etf would be a regulated investment company ric for tax purposes and would not generally pay tax at the fund level the ishares bitcoin trust shares trade on nasdaq, while a spot bitcoin etf would likely trade on a us stock exchange so in summary, the ishares bitcoin trust is a passthrough vehicle that issues shares representing fractional interests in bitcoin, while a spot bitcoin etf would be a regulated investment fund that holds and manages bitcoin directly and issues shares representing an ownership interest in the fund itself the different structures have implications for regulation, taxation and tracking of the underlying bitcoin price hope this helps clarify the differences let me know if you have any other questions

text: the blackrock bitcoin offering is a trust, not an etf here is a summary from claude100k of the s1 at here is a summary of the s1 filing for the ishares bitcoin trust the ishares bitcoin trust will issue shares representing fractional undivided beneficial interests in its net assets, which consist primarily of bitcoin held by a custodian on behalf of the trust the trust seeks to reflect generally the performance of the price of bitcoin the shares are intended to provide investors with an alternative method of investing in bitcoin through the stock market the trusts only recurring expense is expected to be the sponsors fee of of net asset value the sponsor has agreed to assume most of the trusts ordinary expenses shareholders will be treated for tax purposes as if they directly owned a pro rata share of the bitcoin held in the trust trust expenses and the sale of bitcoin to cover those expenses will generally be taxable events to shareholders the shares will be listed and traded on nasdaq under the ticker symbol they will track the price of bitcoin but may trade at a premium or discount to net asset value the trust holds bitcoin that is custody by a bitcoin custodian a portion of bitcoin holdings may also be held with a prime broker to facilitate creations, redemptions, and bitcoin sales to pay the sponsors fee and expenses the trust uses the cme cf bitcoin reference rate new york variant index to value its bitcoin holdings and calculate net asset value that covers the key points regarding the ishares bitcoin trust s1 filing let me know if you have any other questions

text: which copy i mean at a really nitpicky level, one could argue bitcoin isnt dead until all copies of its blockchain, of any height, originating with the same genesis block with a hash value of 000000000019d6689c085ae165831e934ff763ae46a2a6c172b3f1b60a8ce26f, are erased includes all forks not just shutting down nodes, but erasing the raw data whole blockchain from all devices everywhere, even if its just a thumbdrive backup otherwise someone could just spin up a node with an old copy, even at block height 1, and technically claim thats still bitcoin i dont consider restarting from a new genesis block, whether using the original codebase or the current one, still to be bitcoin its an entirely new chain with a new genesis block one could make an argument that would still be bitcoin, i would just disagree then again, i also disagree todays copy people call bitcoin is actually bitcoin, its just a copy of a copy of a copy of a copy crowned bitcoin by most entirely new chains with a new genesis block would be more of a stretch of logic to still call bitcoin though from a more practical level, copies forks of bitcoin die when people stop using them, and no more nodes running that forkcopy one could make a case its died off earlier, when all exchanges everywhere stopped running nodes of the fork, but who knows maybe some group is just using it as a private currency amongst themselves its a tricky question at the end to answer because bitcoin has thousands upon thousands of copies forks only one is typically considered original bitcoin at any given time, usually this is such an overwhelming social consensus that its not even in question ive written about fork resolution soft and hard before, the most useful part of which is a thought exercise regarding a hard fork into two identical copies no changes to the codebase, block structure, etc it helps demonstrate how really the only thing giving one copy more value than the other is network effect id start at hard fork section in the attached tweet below
